I have two cards in my Angular landing page inside a section.
I want a Mammut-style scroll-driven card entrance animation.

CRITICAL MECHANIC — read this before implementing:
This is NOT an IntersectionObserver trigger animation.
This is a SCROLL-MAPPED animation — the card's translateX
position is recalculated on every scroll event as a direct
mathematical function of scrollY. The card moves WITH the
scroll in real time, not just once when entering the viewport.

No external libraries. No GSAP. Vanilla TypeScript + CSS only.
Complete implementation. No stubs. No TODOs.

════════════════════════════════════════════
THE EXACT BEHAVIOR
════════════════════════════════════════════

Phase 1 — BEFORE section reaches viewport:
  Card 1: translateX(-110vw)   ← fully off-screen left
  Card 2: translateX(-110vw)   ← same, slight delay
  Both cards invisible, off-screen left

Phase 2 — ENTERING (section scrolls into view):
  As user scrolls DOWN, cards slide RIGHT
  into their resting position: translateX(0)
  Card 2 lags behind Card 1 by ~80px (stagger)
  This entrance covers a scroll distance of 300px

Phase 3 — RESTING (section fully in view):
  Both cards sit at translateX(0)
  No movement while section is centered in viewport
  This rest zone covers a scroll distance of 200px

Phase 4 — EXITING (user scrolls further down):
  As user scrolls DOWN further, cards slide RIGHT
  off-screen: translateX(110vw)
  Card 1 leads, Card 2 follows with ~80px stagger
  Exit covers a scroll distance of 300px

Phase 5 — REVERSE (user scrolls back UP):
  Everything runs in exact reverse
  Scroll up → cards come back from right → rest → 
  continue back to off-screen left
  The animation is perfectly bidirectional

